Battlestar Galactica (2003–2009) -- t13 Towards a Definition of Twenty-First-Century Epic: Audience Responses to Game of Thrones (2011–2019) and His Dark Materials (2019–) as Epic Television -- tAfterword -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamines representations of ancient epic and epic conventions in film and televisionDemonstrates how adaptation and revision of ancient epic conventions facilitate the articulation of emerging ideals concerning gender, class, race, and nationalityAnalyses recently emerging screen technologies exploring how these technologies have facilitated the capacity of recent films and television to augment the spatiality, distance, and ontological scope identified as crucial components of the epic genreExplores how the conventions of epic have informed televisual production as the medium enters its platinum" age of production and distributionResponds to recent work on the epic genre that has gestured toward speculative fiction as a site for the reception and development of generic conventions characteristic of ancient epicHow do epic tropes shape representations of the ancient world and determine contemporary understandings of historical events? What features of ancient epic persistently emerge in science fiction and fantasy narratives adapted to the screen, and why? How does the different scope of televisual versus cinematic media impact the representation of conventions derived from ancient epic?The international range of contributors to this volume respond to these questions by looking for features of epic outside the traditional realm of Greco-Roman antiquity, including historical films and series, fantasy, science fiction and documentary. By identifying epic conventions on the large and small screen, as well as within a range of speculative fictions in fantastical and futuristic settings, they consider the function of such conventions within their twenty-first-century production contexts."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCivilization, Ancient, in motion pictures. 0aCivilization, Ancient, on television. 0aEpic filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aEpic literaturexAdaptationsxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictures and literature. 0aTelevision and literature. 4aClassics & Ancient History. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh1 aCurley, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCyrino, Monica S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDay, Kirsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Hunter H, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Hunter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Hunter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHobden, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKozak, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagerstädt, Sylvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotter, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotter, Amanda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRea, Jennifer A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSafran, Meredith E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSolomon, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStafford, Emma J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWynell-Mayow, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc